cr_achieved: Most of what Dr. Martin Luther King was advocating has been accomplished. Equality of opportunity has mostly been achieved, so the target was moved to try to enforce equality of results. This desire for special treatment is causing much of the racial unrest tearing this country apart currently.
rr_legacy: NA
rr_nolegacy: The boat people from IndoChina pretty well prove the falsity of the claim that slavery and discrimination has prevented some people from succeeding in modern life. They worked hard, got a decent education, and became productive middle class citizens in a new country. I often wonder if the hatred displayed by other minorities toward people of Asian background is based on jealousy and envy that they were able to overcome the hatred and discrimination to better themselves, thus proving the falsehood of pushing the theory that the legacy of slavery and discrimination is what is holding some people back from enjoying the American dream.

attn_check: The era after the 1900s has been more important
cw_slaverysince: It took more than 100 years to try an eliminate slavery of black people. I experience racism at an early age in the 1950-60s.  Slavery gave birth to racism and continued mistreatment of black people.  America has still not adapted to racism and is still growing in the shedding of this taught and infectious practice of hatred against black people in America, especially the deep south. Slavery is still being dealt with since the Civil War.
cr_progress: The Democratic Party is the most dangerous and biased agent that keep Black people under the realms of racism and former Civil Rights movement. The Democratic party was the Ku Klux Klan and continued to migrate its way to overtake and influence many educated Blacks to join with them under the disguise of civil rights with the intention of destroying black men, families, and ultimately make them believe that their political participation in American politics could only be achieved through this party.  The deceit and double standards practiced by the Democrats later learned by educated Blacks who captured the so-called dream instead achieved personal success by copying the Democratic ways of patronizing Blacks at voting time and blaming the opposition party of hatred and racism to keep Black votes. The Civil Rights movement that led to Dr. Martin Luther King's contribution for equal rights for all was quickly extinguished because he was right, and the population caught hold of the dream. Thus was the end of any type of Civil rights movement in America. The opportunity created by the suffering and sacrifices of Black and White Americans who stood for Civil Rights are the reason the Black People in America, descendants of slaves; are given the choice of receiving education, job opportunity, and other experiences most citizens enjoy, if permitted to when there is an opportunity to choose.  Poverty has prevented many Black people from being successful because of the hatred and racism embedded in local, state, and Federal government; awork in progress until this day! I am proud to be an American from Charleston, SC.  A poor black family; born to a 16 year black teen Mother; lving in a shot gun house next to the railroad. From these meager beginnings, attending public segregated elementary school; snatched up in 1968 to attend forced integration at white high school for four years, and finally my senior year forced integration to another all white school because that community refused to integrate with black people.  The results could have been devastating for me. I made the choice to stay and graduate.  I believe one teacher just passed me so I would not return for another credit to graduate.  Joined the US Army because my draft number was 31.  Instead of the draft I volunteered with hopes of not going to Vietnam.  Now we find that the war was a fraud of politicians.  Clinton was right; Ali was right; many died suffered because of greedy, racist, and political figures.  Thank God a few lived to tell the truth before passing on. Talk about civil rights...God help us all.  By the way I retired from the US Army, Sergeants Major E9 after 25 years and some months; graduated Strayer University 2002 BSBA and 2004 MBA Cum Laude; finally worked with several major Contract companies; retired from Department of Homeland Security as senior security specialist in 2018.  I recently got called back for an opportunity to contribute to my country at department of defense in Nov 2020. I am a senior consultant for an Intelligence and Security Division.  This success I contribute to those that sacrificed and gave their life during the Civil Rights Movement.
rr_legacy: Many of these people, like me, do not have the education, live in poverty, and lack parental guidance and may do not know direction to move in after being bombarded with fiction, television, society domination and lies. There is no standard that is practiced.  Church has closed their doors.  School has taken on a secular pathway to destruction and undisciplined way of life. Nothing is sacred. Respect for one another is an afterthought.

The country thought very differently than we do today.  Each state was considered sovereign but they depended on each other.  The south wanted to export goods which could get them better money than the industrial states paid.  The north wanted the south's money - they wanted to control production and execution.  The south didn't want to pay the price.  The north wanted control.  Slavery or not, control and power was more important as was all the money involved.  Those elements led to the war, not simply slavery.  The north didn't necessarily want to free the slaves, they wanted the south.

The black citizens did get much out of the war because the north didn't want them and there were no economy in the south. attn_check: The era after the 1900s has been more important
cw_slaverysince: Every state signing up to secede listed it as the reason for doing so.  'State's rights' is the nonsense they made up after the War to explain their actions.  The big mystery will always be why so many dirt poor white people, whose own labor was devalued by slavery, fought to keep it.  As Mamma Gump said: "stupid is as stupid does."
cr_progress: In a nutshell, white backlash.  By the '60s, working class white people in cities like Boston already had a sense that they were going no farther, that their schools were crap and their children were behind the 8 ball; the idea of busing them to crappier schools so students from those schools could take their place seemed like a betrayal.  Were they also racists?  Of course, but their primary objections were perfectly rational and well grounded.
rr_legacy:
In the New Deal, there were a lot of carve outs to the minimum wage and the right to organize, demanded by Southern Democrats (whose descendants are all now Republicans).  Servants were not subject to minimum wage - so the nice ladies who cleaned your house, washed your clothes, cooked your meals, tended your babies and elders, had no say in how many hours they had to work to make whatever you'd agreed to pay them per week.  Neither did their husbands, who worked your fields, chopped your tobacco, cared for your horses and cows.

In the Depression, we created a lot of programs aimed at destitute white women whose husbands had run off, and that model stuck, making it impossible for low income families to stay together and get public assistance: all those high rise housing projects like Cabrini Green in Chicago were designed to make husbands disappear.  Stuyvesant Town in NYC was aimed at lower middle class white GIs coming home, and it remains a great place to live.
And here's the biggie: the GI Bill.  It was largely unaccessible to Black vets.  They couldn't buy in any of the new suburbs being built, and the places where they COULD buy were often deemed unworthy of loans: talk about Catch 22.  The intergenerational wealth created by the GI Bill for middle class white Americans is something that very few of us understand - though the last 40 years of "trickle down" economics is starting (hopefully) to wake some of us the hell up.

attn_check: The era after the 1900s has been more important
cw_slaverysince: It really hasn't been. At least not in any way that worked towards ensuring former slaves and subsequent generations were given full equity under the law and our Constitution. Denial, guilt and fear post slavery contributed to the enactment of first Jim Crow laws, and post-1960s Civil Rights era institutionalized racism practices all of which were made to keep black Americans in a perpetual state of struggle due to barriers that were constructed in order to keep them from achieving what they are entitled to both by man made laws and the unwritten laws of human ethics. However, as much as I have spent my life fighting for equal rights for all one thing that needs to be addressed simultaneously by any person or group in regards to racism is sexism as well. For the last forty years I have been advocating that we address and work towards fixing the issues of racism and sexism as one issue because you cannot fix one without fixing the other. They are linked. In the last few years the term intersectionality was coined, and although accurate that is the concept I have been aware of and speaking up about for the last forty years.
cr_progress: Mostly laws written and unwritten steeped in fear and perpetuated through the cyclical indoctrination of ideologies passed down to each generation. The gears of ignorance, fear and prejudice in America never stop turning it seems.
rr_legacy: Primarily due to inaction and accountability by republican politicians and the right wing agenda black Americans still have to work twice as hard to achieve half as much. However, racism is just one of many problems still plaguing America today under the wider umbrella of classism. The wealthy and powerful know this. They know classism covers a wide swath of those they deem as undesirables.
